sec.p:
The insect order 
Trichoptera
(caddisflies) is composed of species whose eggs, larvae, and pupae are particularly abundant and diverse in freshwater, whereas their adults are generally terrestrial. Most caddisflies species have one generation per year (univoltine) and are egg-laying (oviparous) (

). Larvae of the different species can live under many different ecological conditions and habitats (

). There are more than 17,000 species worldwide (

).

In Morocco , the trichopterological fauna includes 85 species distributed in two suborders: The Annulipalpia include 33 species distributed over 5 families and the Integripalpia comprise 52 species divided among 9 families, including the family Calamoceratidae (
,
).

Globally, the Calamoceratidae include 198 species in 8 genera:
Anisocentropus McLachlan 1863
;
Phylloicus Müller 1880
;
Banyallarga Navás 1916
;
Ganonema McLachlan 1866
;
Ascalaphomerus Walker 1852
;
Calamoceras Brauer 1865
;
Georgium Fischer 1964
; and
Heteroplectron McLachlan 1871
(
; Morse unpublished data). Among these genera,
Calamoceras
is the only genus found in the West Palearctic Region and includes only two species (Graff et al. 2008):
Calamoceras marsupus Brauer 1865
and
Calamoceras illiesi Malicky & Kumanski 1974
.
Calamoceras marsupus
occurs in France , the Iberic-Macaronesian region, the Pyrenees, the Western Highlands, the Western Plains (Graff et al. 2008), and Morocco (
;
;
;
;
;
;
) and has a preference for intermittent watercourses (
).
Calamoceras illiesi
occurs in Bulgaria (
), Croatia , Greece (
), Turkey (
), and the western and southern Caucasus (
).

